      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study yielded GCI < 2.1% for hemolysis index at all operating points. Richardson extrapolation applied with observed order 1.94. AchievedLevel 3 exceeds requirement. Documented in VR-02."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions documented with sufficient detail to reproduce; temperature, flow rate, fluid properties, and pump speed recorded; achievedLevel >= 2.",
      "rationale": "In-vitro test conditions fully documented: bovine blood at 22°C, hematocrit 33±1%, pump speeds 2000–4000 RPM, flow rates 2–6 L/min. All five operating points recorded with calibrated instrumentation. Test conducted at standard atmospheric pressure in a temperature-controlled laboratory. Ambient temperature was held at 22°C throughout; no variation across the clinical operating environment temperature range (18–26°C in the OR) was introduced. Humidity and EMI conditions of the test laboratory are not reported and were not matched to OR deployment conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric defined; CFD-predicted NIH within 15% of measured values at all operating points; achievedLevel >= 2.",
      "rationale": "Relative hemolysis index RH computed at each of five operating points. CFD predictions within 12% of measured NIH across all points. Acceptance criterion of RH < 1 met at all points. Comparison performed against laboratory data at 22°C only; no comparison data exist for the full OR temperature range or under EMI conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (NIH, RH) directly maps to clinical hemolysis endpoint; achievedLevel >= 2.",
      "rationale": "Normalized index of hemolysis and relative hemolysis index are the accepted regulatory QoIs for CPB hemolysis assessment per FDA guidance. Both are directly linked to red blood cell damage and clinical outcome. QoI relevance is high and well-established in the literature."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry, fluid, and operating conditions representative of CPB COU; achievedLevel >= 2.",
      "rationale": "Validation used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, bovine blood as an accepted hemolysis surrogate, and operating conditions spanning the clinical CPB range (2–6 L/min, 2000–4000 RPM). Geometry and boundary conditions match the COU. However, the validation environment (22°C controlled laboratory, atmospheric pressure, no EMI) does not fully represent the OR deployment environment where temperature may vary 18–26°C, ambient pressure may differ at altitude-capable centers, and electrosurgical EMI is present. This environmental gap is not addressed by any linked sensitivity study."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence criteria documented; mass and momentum residuals < 1e-5; achievedLevel >= 1.",
      "rationale": "Steady-state RANS simulations converged to mass and momentum residuals below 1e-5. Convergence monitored via NIH probe; variation < 0.3% over final 500 iterations. Solver settings documented in simulation log files."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by independent analyst; boundary condition inputs verified against test data; achievedLevel >= 1.",
      "rationale": "Independent peer review of simulation setup performed by a second analyst. Boundary conditions verified against experimental records. No use errors identified. Review documented in project quality record QR-2024-07."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model and hemolysis power-law model selection justified with literature support; achievedLevel >= 2.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on demonstrated performance in rotating machinery hemolysis literature. Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model applied with Bludszuweit modification. Model form selection justified by published benchmark comparisons. Blood viscosity modeled as Newtonian at 33% hematocrit, consistent with CPB conditions. Model form does not account for potential viscosity changes due to temperature variation across the OR environment range."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model inputs characterized with uncertainty bounds; blood viscosity, density, and pump geometry tolerances documented; achievedLevel >= 2.",
      "rationale": "Blood viscosity (3.5 mPa·s at 22°C, 33% Hct), density (1050 kg/m³), and pump geometry nominal dimensions with manufacturing tolerances documented. Inlet velocity profiles derived from calibrated flow meters. Input uncertainty propagation performed via ±5% perturbation study on key parameters. Temperature dependence of blood viscosity across the OR range (18–26°C) was not included in the input uncertainty characterization; viscosity can vary approximately 15% over this range, which is larger than the perturbation study bounds used."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test fluid characterized with hematocrit and sample provenance documented; n >= 3 independent samples; achievedLevel >= 1.",
      "rationale": "Bovine blood from certified supplier, hematocrit 33±1% confirmed by centrifugation. Three independent blood batches used across the five operating points. Sample age < 24 hours at time of test. Sample characterization documented in laboratory notebook LN-2023-CPB-04."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters demonstrated equivalent to test conditions for all primary QoI drivers; achievedLevel >= 2.",
      "rationale": "Flow rates, pump speeds, fluid properties, and inlet boundary conditions in the CFD model confirmed equivalent to measured test conditions within instrument uncertainty. Dimensional equivalency of the pump geometry verified by CMM measurement. Equivalency established for all parameters tested in the laboratory at 22°C and atmospheric pressure. Equivalency of input parameters under OR deployment conditions (temperature 18–26°C, variable ambient pressure, EMI-exposed instrumentation) has not been established, as no testing was conducted outside the single laboratory environmental condition."
    }
